一、圖書作者與內容簡介：<BR>
     It all begins with Violet and Finch’s meeting each other on the ledge of the bell tower at school, and working as a pair in their U.S. Geography class. Violet and Finch gradually become each other’s company, and bright places. Two main characters have their own issues as teenagers. Fortunately, Violet starts to drive back on her right track of life with Finch’s companionship. Yet frustratingly, Finch can’t get out of his dark world.<br />
<br />

<BR>
二、內容摘錄：<BR>
     We alternate choosing places to go, but we also have to be willing to go where the road takes us. This means the grand, the small, the bizarre, the poetic, the beautiful, the ugly, the surprising. Just like life. But absolutely, unconditionally, resolutely nothing ordinary.(p.43)<br />
<br />
     “We can’t always see what others don’t want us to. Especially when they go to great lengths to hide it.”  “ ‘You’re a survivor, your survival—your emotional survival—will depend on how you learn to cope with your tragedy. The bad news: Surviving this will be the second worst experience of your life. The good news: The worst is already over.’ ”(p.347-348)<br />
<br />
     I don’t need to worry that Finch and I never filmed our wanderings. The thing I realize is that it’s not what you take, it’s what you leave.(p.376)<br />
<br />

<BR>
三、我的觀點：<BR>
     When I read this novel at night each day, it made me feel peaceful and it made me think a lot. It immersed me in a world where a lot of meanings beneath the surface. Our life consists of many terms of emotions like joy, rage, sadness and happiness. Since these are inescapable, why not just embrace them all? I always think of life as a symphony that sings our experiences, good ones and bad ones. As I finished this book, I once again made up my mind to live out every moment. I am willing to go where the life takes me and having no regrets.<br />
<br />
     In the story, Finch leads Violet to bright places, and Violet gives Finch a reason to live on. Therefore, I do believe people can help one another as long as we care more and give more. As Finch hopes “ It will be a world of compassion, of neighbor loving neighbor, of student loving student or at least treating one another with respect. No judgment. No name-calling. No more, no more, no more,” I can hear Finch’s calling for help, but the truth is that he never gets the chance to speak it out. I assume that this book helps readers see who needs help, and the ways to get help, though people around Finch and Finch himself fail to do so. It is against my wish that at the end of the story, failing to ask for and get help form Violet and his family, Finch dives deep down into the lake as a way to escape his melancholy life. It is so true that Violet says at the end of the book: “The thing I realize is that it’s not what you take, it’s what you leave.” People around Finch cannot help him out of his problems, yet, he teaches Violet and the other characters to have the courage to ask for help and have the mind to care and respect. Thus, though Finch leaves, he does leave behind valuable lessons for us, and hopefully takes away discrimination and disrespect for the differentiation. When my reading lines paused here, I told myself that I would never be afraid to show my true feelings, to care more about the people I love, and I thank to Finch’s “No time like the present.”<br />
<br />
     Finch’s rule for wandering for the geography project is: “We alternate choosing places to go, but we also have to be willing to go where the road takes us. This means the grand, the small, the bizarre, the poetic, the beautiful, the ugly, the surprising. Just like life. But absolutely, unconditionally, resolutely nothing ordinary.” I love what Finch says about the meaning of our life. Whatever we would have in our life, we need to live and grow with it. Ernest Hemingway once said, “The world breaks everyone, and afterward, many are strong at the broken places.” Maybe that is what the author tries to tell her readers, “ ‘You’re a survivor, and as that unwelcome designation implies, your survival—your emotional survival—will depend on how you learn to cope with your tragedy. The bad news: Surviving this will be the second worst experience of your life. The good news: The worst is already over.’ ” I believe the good news is the place we stand up from again and we all learn something from the survival. Just like Finch, things we have to take away are the regrets or self-blame that found in life, and we leave all our beautiful footprints and good qualities rooted in life. Eventually, all of us would be like Violet, who will live out her life once again, because Finch has shown her how to live, why to live, and what to live for.      <br />
<br />
     British poet John Donne said “No man is an island” nearly 400 years ago, therefore, I suppose it’s human nature to help, care, and support one another. If our world is so indifferent like what Finch describes, then we should start to put ourselves in other people’s shoes. Wherever there is diversity, be respectful and open-minded. Whenever there is distress, be helpful and positive. I think it is the indifference that Finch wants to take away and the understanding to leave for us.<br />
<br />

<BR>
